{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17603293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17603293"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:35:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:35:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15735"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15735"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.03,0.33,0.61,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67322"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8426"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15735"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52774"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1638"},{"type":"tags","id":"1793"},{"type":"tags","id":"3829"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7037"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20282"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22544"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67322"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with three months of intermittent right-sided pelvic pain. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Bimanual examination reveals a mobile, non-tender right adnexal mass. Pelvic ultrasound shows a 6 cm right ovarian mass containing hyperechoic components and areas of acoustic shadowing. A plain X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient undergoes laparoscopic ovarian cystectomy. Histological examination of the specimen reveals a cyst lined by keratinised squamous epithelium containing skin appendages, hair follicles, and tooth buds\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Choriocarcinoma","Dysgerminoma","Immature teratoma","Mature cystic teratoma","Yolk sac tumour"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological findings of keratinised squamous epithelium, skin appendages, hair follicles, and tooth buds are characteristic of a \u003Cstrong\u003Emature cystic teratoma\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as a dermoid cyst. The teeth can be seen on the plain X-ray.  These tumours are the most common ovarian germ cell tumours, accounting for approximately 20% of all ovarian tumours. They contain well-differentiated tissues from all three germ cell layers (ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm) and typically occur in young women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChoriocarcinomas\u003C/strong\u003E show a distinctive biphasic pattern with syncytiotrophoblasts and cytotrophoblasts without the organised tissue differentiation seen here. They are highly malignant and typically present with elevated beta-human chorionic gonadotropin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDysgerminomas\u003C/strong\u003E are malignant germ cell tumours that typically appear as sheets of uniform cells with clear cytoplasm separated by fibrous bands containing lymphocytes. They do not show the organised tissue differentiation seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmature teratomas\u003C/strong\u003E contain immature or embryonal elements, particularly neuroectodermal tissues, and do not show the well-differentiated tissues seen in this case. They are typically seen in younger patients and are considered malignant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYolk sac tumours\u003C/strong\u003E show various patterns including microcystic/reticular pattern, endodermal sinus pattern, and the presence of Schiller-Duval bodies. They are highly malignant and typically occur in children and young adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMature cystic teratomas are usually benign and can be managed with ovarian cystectomy in young women who wish to preserve fertility. The presence of mature elements from multiple germ cell layers, particularly the characteristic finding of skin and its appendages, is diagnostic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mature cystic teratomas are the most common ovarian germ cell tumour, containing well-differentiated tissues from all three germ cell layers.","The presence of skin, hair, and teeth on histology is pathognomonic for mature cystic teratoma.","Mature cystic teratomas typically occur in young women and are usually benign."],"references":["Cong L, Wang S, Yeung SY, Lee JHS, Chung JPW, Chan DYL. Mature Cystic Teratoma: An Integrated Review. Int J Mol Sci. 2023 Mar 24;24(7):6141. doi: 10.3390/ijms24076141. PMID: 37047114; PMCID: PMC10093990.","Momenimovahed Z, Tiznobaik A, Taheri S, Salehiniya H. Ovarian cancer in the world: epidemiology and risk factors. Int J Womens Health. 2019 Apr 30;11:287-299. doi: 10.2147/IJWH.S197604. PMID: 31118829; PMCID: PMC6500433","Cho KR, Shih IeM. Ovarian cancer. Annu Rev Pathol. 2009;4:287-313. doi: 10.1146/annurev.pathol.4.110807.092246. PMID: 18842102; PMCID: PMC2679364","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52774"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15735"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21289"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21289"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/gUp3j2q4spC3TB0VzyOcpqyJfdUZY1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/gUp3j2q4spC3TB0VzyOcpqyJfdUZY1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":696,"height":543}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52774"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T20:44:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T20:45:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8426"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67322"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology